Bovespa Advances for a Third Day on Brazilian Retail Sales, U.S. Jobs Data

-- B y   N e y   H a y a s h i   a n d   A l e x a n d e r   C u a d r o s
-- 
2011-08-11T20:52:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-11/bovespa-advances-third-day-on-brazilian-interest-rate-bets-u-s-jobs-data.html
The Bovespa stock index posted its
biggest three-day gain in more than two years after reports
showed Brazil’s retail sales slowed less than forecast in June
and unemployment claims unexpectedly fell in the U.S., the
country’s second-biggest trading partner.  Braskem SA,  Latin America ’s largest petrochemicals
producer, surged after it reported quarterly earnings that
exceeded analysts’ estimates. Homebuilder MRV Engenharia &
Participacoes SA advanced after saying it will buy back 10
million of its common shares during the next year.  The Bovespa rose 3.8 percent to 53,343.11 at the close of
trading at 4:15 p.m. New York time. Fifty-four stocks rose on
the index, while nine dropped. The gauge jumped 9.6 percent
since Aug. 8, the most since May 2009. The real strengthened 0.1
percent to 1.6234 per dollar.  “We had some good news today, like the jobless-claims data
in the U.S,”  Felipe Casotti , who helps manage 1.2 billion reais
($739 million) at Maxima Asset Management, said in a telephone
interview from  Rio de Janeiro . “There’s too much volatility in
the markets right now. Stocks go down 5 percent one day and go
up 5 percent in the following day. We’ll keep going like this
until there are clearer signs that global economic recovery is
really back on track.”  Applications for jobless benefits in the U.S. decreased
7,000 in the week ended Aug. 6 to 395,000, the fewest since
early April, the Labor Department said today in  Washington .
Economists forecast 405,000 claims, according to the median
estimate in a Bloomberg News survey.  U.S. stocks rallied after the report was released. All 10
groups in the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index advanced.  Brazil Retail Sales  Retail sales in  Brazil  increased 0.2 percent in June, the
national statistics agency said in Rio de Janeiro. Sales growth
was expected to remain stagnant, according to the median
estimate in a Bloomberg survey of 33 analysts, after a revised
0.7 percent expansion in May. Sales rose 7.1 percent from a year
ago, beating a median estimate of 6.4 percent.  Braskem gained 5.6 percent to 16.15 reais. The company
posted second-quarter net income of 420 million reais, according
to a regulatory filing. The average estimate of five analysts in
a Bloomberg survey was for net income on an adjusted basis of
388.6 million reais.  MRV gained 5.8 percent to 11.67 reais.  The Bovespa entered a  bear market  on July 27 after plunging
20 percent from its bull-market peak in November. The measure
has since extended that slide to 27 percent.  As of Aug. 8, Brazil’s benchmark equity index traded at 8
times analysts’ earnings estimates, the lowest since February
2009, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. That compared to
a ratio of 11.6 for the Shanghai Composite Index, 5.8 for
 Russia ’s Micex and 13.9 for  India ’s Sensex.  Traders moved 8.18 billion reais in stocks in Sao Paulo
yesterday, data compiled by Bloomberg show. That compares to a
daily average this year of 6.36 billion reais through Aug. 3,
according to data from the exchange.  To contact the reporter on this story:
